<div class="container" style="margin-top: 1em;">

	<div class="row">

		<div id="primary" class="col-xs-12 col-md-9">
			<div class="breadcrumbs"><!-- Breadcrumb NavXT 6.6.0 -->
<a title="Go to Ryerson University Library." href="https://library.ryerson.ca" class="home">Ryerson University Library</a> &#187; <a title="Go to News." href="https://library.ryerson.ca/blog/" class="post-root post post-post">News</a> &#187; News</div>
							<p>This category must be assigned to posts that are to appear on the news feed on the Library&#8217;s home page.</p>
			
			
<article id="post-37309" class="post-37309 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-news">
			<header class="entry-header">
			<h1 class="entry-title"><a href="https://library.ryerson.ca/blog/2020/11/ryerson-university-library-partners-with-the-aga-khan-museum-to-create-digital-experiences-for-pilot-project-and-the-museums-remastered-exhibit/">Ryerson University Library partners with the Aga Khan Museum to create digital experiences for pilot project and the Museum’s Remastered exhibit</a></h1>
		</header><!-- .entry-header -->
	
	<div class="entry-content">

				<div class="entry-meta">
			<span class="sep">Posted on </span><a href="https://library.ryerson.ca/blog/2020/11/ryerson-university-library-partners-with-the-aga-khan-museum-to-create-digital-experiences-for-pilot-project-and-the-museums-remastered-exhibit/" title="9:00 am" rel="bookmark"><time class="entry-date" datetime="2020-11-30T09:00:15-05:00" pubdate>November 30, 2020</time></a><span class="by-author"> <span class="sep"> by </span> <span class="author vcard"><a class="url fn n" href="https://library.ryerson.ca/blog/author/jenna-charlton/" title="View all posts by Ryerson Library" rel="author">Ryerson Library</a></span></span>		</div><!-- .entry-meta -->
		
		<figure id="attachment_37394" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-37394" style="width: 1200px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading="lazy" class="size-full wp-image-37394 jetpack-lazy-image" src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner.png" alt="Image of man on horse reaching up" width="1200" height="392" data-lazy-srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner.png 1200w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner-300x98.png 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner-650x212.png 650w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner-150x49.png 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner-768x251.png 768w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" data-lazy-src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner.png?is-pending-load=1" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7"><noscript><img loading="lazy" class="size-full wp-image-37394" src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner.png" alt="Image of man on horse reaching up" width="1200" height="392" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner.png 1200w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner-300x98.png 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner-650x212.png 650w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner-150x49.png 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/agakhan_banner-768x251.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" /></noscript><figcaption id="caption-attachment-37394" class="wp-caption-text">Courtesy of the Aga Khan Museum</figcaption></figure>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Ryerson University Library has partnered with the Aga Khan Museum in a creative collaboration that harnesses digital technology to create innovative experiences for the Museum’s exciting new </span><a href="https://www.agakhanmuseum.org/exhibitions/remastered"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Remastered</span></i></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> exhibition.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Aga Khan Museum recently launched it’s vibrant </span><a href="https://www.agakhanmuseum.org/exhibitions/remastered"><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Remastered</span></i></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> exhibition—November 7 to March 21, 2021—showcasing 11 classic Islamic manuscript paintings complemented by 40 digital interventions.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The digital interventions are the work of Library Collaboratory team members, Lead Developer Michael Carter-Arlt, Web Developer and Support Technician </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">Jae Duk Seo, with Information Technology Services Head Fangmin Wang and Web Services Librarian Sally Wilson acting as administrative consultants on the project.  </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In collaboration with the Museum and exhibition curator Dr. Michael Chagnon, the Library team developed new ways to experience the historic manuscripts, introducing alternative learning opportunities through the exploration of digital technologies.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“The </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Remastered</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> exhibition has given us the valuable opportunity to reimagine how we interpret classic Islamic artworks using modern technology available at the Ryerson Library,” says Carter-Arlt. “The intention of this project is to tell a story for each artwork, and in doing so provide a greater understanding through interactive digital media.”</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">…..</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Library’s partnership with the Aga Khan Museum began in 2019 when the Museum approached the Library about</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> creating unique learning experiences using Virtual Reality (VR), Augmented Reality (AR) and Mixed Reality (MR) technologies.  </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Following initial meetings, the Library and Museum worked together on an exploratory research project, funded by the Canada Council for the Arts, which sought to develop and assess digital and experiential learning resources that would help to increase classroom engagement, and expand access to collections beyond in-person visits to the Museum. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Aga Khan Museum supplied the Library with high resolution photographs and descriptions of three objects from their collection, including: an astrolabe (astronomical instrument), an illuminated and illustrated leaf from a manuscript, and a green ceramic bottle. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The Library team then used digital and emerging technologies to create new experiences that could be tested for their engagement and educational value.</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In total, four experiences for the three objects were developed. They included: an AR animation with translations and audio for the leaf of the manuscript; AR and Looking Glass (holographic) experiences for the green ceramic bottle; and an acrylic replica astrolabe, which could be taken apart and rebuilt. </span></p>
<figure id="attachment_37388" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-37388" style="width: 500px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-37388 jetpack-lazy-image" src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe-300x225.png" alt="Image of original astrolabe (ancient watch). Courtesy of the Aga Khan Museum" width="500" height="375" data-lazy-srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe-300x225.png 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe-650x488.png 650w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe-150x113.png 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe-768x576.png 768w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe.png 1000w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" data-lazy-src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe-300x225.png?is-pending-load=1" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7"><noscript><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-37388" src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe-300x225.png" alt="Image of original astrolabe (ancient watch). Courtesy of the Aga Khan Museum" width="500" height="375" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe-300x225.png 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe-650x488.png 650w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe-150x113.png 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe-768x576.png 768w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Astrolabe.png 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></noscript><figcaption id="caption-attachment-37388" class="wp-caption-text">Image of original astrolabe (astronomical instrument). Courtesy of the Aga Khan Museum</figcaption></figure>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<figure id="attachment_37389" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-37389" style="width: 500px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-37389 jetpack-lazy-image" src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe-300x225.png" alt="Acrylic replica of the astrolabe. Laser cut at the Library Collaboratory." width="500" height="375" data-lazy-srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe-300x225.png 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe-650x488.png 650w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe-150x113.png 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe-768x576.png 768w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe.png 1000w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" data-lazy-src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe-300x225.png?is-pending-load=1" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7"><noscript><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-37389" src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe-300x225.png" alt="Acrylic replica of the astrolabe. Laser cut at the Library Collaboratory." width="500" height="375" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe-300x225.png 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe-650x488.png 650w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe-150x113.png 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe-768x576.png 768w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/replica-astrolabe.png 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></noscript><figcaption id="caption-attachment-37389" class="wp-caption-text">Acrylic replica of the astrolabe. Laser cut at the Library Collaboratory.</figcaption></figure>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Library team members, Sally Wilson, E-learning and Accessibility Services Librarian Kelly Dermody, and Operations Specialist Cristina Pietropaolo then conducted focus groups to further understand the engagement impacts and potential of the digital resources for in-class learning, as well as increased access to museum collections.   </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“The purpose of this project was to translate select items of the Museum’s collection from their physical confines to digital formats using Augmented Reality (AR) and other technologies,” says Pietropaolo. “The long-term intention of this work is to facilitate accessible and meaningful education around these objects for both educators and their students in the classroom, as well as for members of the public in an effort to transform and enhance access to arts and culture education.”</span></p>
<figure id="attachment_37396" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-37396" style="width: 500px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading="lazy" class="size-full wp-image-37396 jetpack-lazy-image" src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Original-vase-1.png" alt="Image of original green vase. Courtesy of the Aga Khan Museum" width="500" height="500" data-lazy-srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Original-vase-1.png 500w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Original-vase-1-300x300.png 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Original-vase-1-150x150.png 150w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" data-lazy-src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Original-vase-1.png?is-pending-load=1" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7"><noscript><img loading="lazy" class="size-full wp-image-37396" src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Original-vase-1.png" alt="Image of original green vase. Courtesy of the Aga Khan Museum" width="500" height="500" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Original-vase-1.png 500w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Original-vase-1-300x300.png 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/Original-vase-1-150x150.png 150w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" /></noscript><figcaption id="caption-attachment-37396" class="wp-caption-text">Image of original green bottle. Courtesy of the Aga Khan Museum</figcaption></figure>
<figure id="attachment_37397" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-37397" style="width: 650px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading="lazy" class="size-large wp-image-37397 jetpack-lazy-image" src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase-650x488.png" alt="Augment reality image of vase. Educators and students can use mobile devises to see, interact, learn and experience the object." width="650" height="488" data-lazy-srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase-650x488.png 650w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase-300x225.png 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase-150x113.png 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase-768x576.png 768w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase.png 1000w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px" data-lazy-src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase-650x488.png?is-pending-load=1" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7"><noscript><img loading="lazy" class="size-large wp-image-37397" src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase-650x488.png" alt="Augment reality image of vase. Educators and students can use mobile devises to see, interact, learn and experience the object." width="650" height="488" srcset="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase-650x488.png 650w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase-300x225.png 300w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase-150x113.png 150w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase-768x576.png 768w, https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/augmented-vase.png 1000w" sizes="(max-width: 650px) 100vw, 650px" /></noscript><figcaption id="caption-attachment-37397" class="wp-caption-text">Augmented reality image of bottle. Educators and students can use mobile devices to see, interact, learn and experience the object.</figcaption></figure>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The work which began in 2019 is ongoing as Library team members continue to investigate opportunities for digital and experiential learning in the context of gallery, library, archives and museum education.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">……</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">In April 2020, the Aga Khan Museum once again approached the Library to collaborate on the </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Remastered</span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;"> exhibit, curated by Dr. Michael Chagnon. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The task: to develop digital experiences to accompany ancient Islamic manuscripts for the exhibit. To complete the project, the Library was given exclusive access to high resolution folios in order to rework and reimagine them in digital formats. The result was 40 new experiences including: seven animations, five 3D holograms, five digital restorations, and 23 interactive folios. The Library and Museum also received a generous loan from </span><a href="https://lookingglassfactory.com/"><span style="font-weight: 400;">Looking Glass Factory</span></a><span style="font-weight: 400;"> to assist in the display of the holographic images.</span></p>
<figure id="attachment_37331" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-37331" style="width: 314px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-37331 size-full jetpack-lazy-image" src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/AKM28811OPT_2.gif" alt width="314" height="550" data-lazy-src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/AKM28811OPT_2.gif?is-pending-load=1" srcset="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7"><noscript><img loading="lazy" class="wp-image-37331 size-full" src="https://library.ryerson.ca/wp-content/uploads/AKM28811OPT_2.gif" alt="" width="314" height="550" /></noscript><figcaption id="caption-attachment-37331" class="wp-caption-text">Salih Takes Mah-Pervin on Board . Fol. 29r from a manuscript of Tuhfet ul-Leta’if Turkey, Istanbul, 1593–1594. Opaque watercolour, gold, and ink on paper. AKM280.11 Digital intervention by Michael Carter-Arlt.</figcaption></figure>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">The digital elements, now part of the </span><i><span style="font-weight: 400;">Remastered </span></i><span style="font-weight: 400;">exhibit, enhance the overall learning and storytelling experience for visitors through digital restoration, innovative engagement elements and new digitally enhanced explorations.  </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">“We are very excited to partner with the Aga Khan Museum. It has been a wonderful opportunity to bring the Library’s role in interdisciplinary research, knowledge sharing and digital information tools to this unique learning environment,” says Chief Librarian Carol Shepstone. “This project is an excellent example of how the GLAM sectors (galleries, libraries, archives and museums) can come together to leverage unique expertise and shared goals.”</span></p>
		
		
		<footer class="entry-meta">
			<span>This entry was posted in <a href="https://library.ryerson.ca/blog/category/news/" rel="category tag">News</a> by <a href="https://library.ryerson.ca/blog/author/jenna-charlton/">Ryerson Library</a>. Bookmark the <a href="https://library.ryerson.ca/blog/2020/11/ryerson-university-library-partners-with-the-aga-khan-museum-to-create-digital-experiences-for-pilot-project-and-the-museums-remastered-exhibit/" title="Permalink to Ryerson University Library partners with the Aga Khan Museum to create digital experiences for pilot project and the Museum’s Remastered exhibit" rel="bookmark">permalink</a>.</span>					</footer><!-- .entry-meta -->

